      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\cognitive-taxonomy-vscode-ext\\README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Cognitive Taxonomy Protocol — VS Code Extension\n2: \n3: A five-colour architectural taxonomy that shifts code comprehension from **System 2** (linear reading) to **System 1** (pattern recognition).\n4: \n5: ## How It Works\n6: \n7: Toggle with `Ctrl+Shift+T` (or `Cmd+Shift+T` on Mac). Watch the bottom-right status bar: `Taxonomy: ON` / `Taxonomy: OFF`.\n8: \n9: ### Taxonomy Mode\n10: \n11: - Each line gets a **coloured left border** by architectural category\n12: - Hover over any line to see a **tooltip** explaining what it does\n13: - VS Code Dark+ token colours are neutralised to grey\n14: - Comments stay green (preserved)\n15: \n16: ### Categories\n17: \n18: | Colour | Category | What It Means |\n19: |--------|----------|---------------|\n20: | Blue | Blueprint | Data structures — what we're building |\n21: | Green | Plumbing | Infrastructure — how it connects |\n22: | Orange | Transaction | Logic flow — how data moves |\n23: | Red | Constraint | Hard limits — what cannot be exceeded |\n24: | Purple | Pedagogy | Assessment — how this is graded |\n25: \n26: ## Install (Development)\n27: \n28: ```bash\n29: cd cognitive-taxonomy-vscode-ext\n30: npm install\n31: npm run compile\n32: ```\n33: \n34: Then in VS Code:\n35: 1. Press `F5` to launch Extension Development Host\n36: 2. Open a Python file\n37: 3. Press `Ctrl+Shift+T` to toggle taxonomy mode\n38: \n39: ## Install (Packaged)\n40: \n41: ```bash\n42: npm install -g @vscode/vsce\n43: vsce package\n44: # Installs cognitive-taxonomy-protocol-0.0.1.vsix\n45: ```\n46: \n47: ## Grounded In\n48: \n49: - **Kahneman (2011)** — System 1/System 2 dual-process theory\n50: - **Miller (1956)** — Working memory limit: 7±2 chunks (five colours stays within)\n51: - **Sarkar (2015)** — Syntax highlighting improves comprehension for novices\n52: - **Asenov et al. (2016)** — Richer visualisations reduce comprehension time by 75%\n53: - **MITRE ATT&CK** — Taxonomy-based visual compression transformed cybersecurity\n\n(End of file - total 53 lines)\n</content>",
      "status": "success",
