      "output": "Found 1156 matches (showing first 100)\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Downloads\\_chat 9.txt:\n  Line 7: [12/05/2025, 18:23:15] Fizzy: @⁨Andie⁩ I also created the shell for the frontend jira project: https://getawayai.atlassian.net/jira/software/projects/SCRUM/boards/1\r\n\n  Line 137: [17/05/2025, 16:14:04] Andie: The Pica framework remains Pica's open-source project under the GPL. You are building on it, not claiming ownership of it.\n\n  Line 222: For your GetAway AI agent project, Bright Data acts as a powerful data source tool, specifically enabling your agent to gather information from web pages that do not offer structured APIs for the data you need. It essentially provides \"Web Data Access as a Service.\"\r\n\n  Line 630: [14/07/2025, 13:07:31] Andie: Hi @⁨Fizzy⁩ ! Happy for us to regroup later today. Unfortunately I haven’t been able to make much project from the last time we spoke due to some development blockers that I still need to document on Jira self. But it’d defo great to touch base and re-align exactly.\r\n\n  Line 877: The hackathon project can be a demonstration of a subset of GetAway's capabilities. It's a vertical slice.\n\n  Line 879: *Strategy*: Build the hackathon submission as a minimal, standalone project focused only on the hotel ranking/recommendation problem using Nuitée LiteAPI. Do not include any code or logic for other parts of GetAway (e.g., full group management, complex multi-component trip planning, integration with all your external APIs/KG).\n\n  Line 887: *Use of Open-Source Base Models*: For the LLM component in the hackathon project, use a publicly available model (e.g., Qwen3, Gemma 3, or even a smaller Phi-4) rather than a custom-trained, proprietary SLM. The focus is on the agentic application of the LLM. Or well just Gemini isn't it! ‎<This message was edited>\r\n\n  Line 1010: https://getawayai.atlassian.net/jira/software/projects/SCRUM/boards/1\r\n\n  Line 1130: [13/01/2026, 14:49:26] Andie: So u have no 2nd monitor to u know extend, mirror, project, smart tv casting, Amazon fire stick/chrome cast\r\n\n\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Downloads\\_chat 8.txt:\n  Line 216: This is statement. We are three photographers and working on personal projects for one exhibition\r\n\n  Line 456: [19/04/2024, 07:03:16] Marquis A. Caines (BYPCardiff): Build up a team and let the project fly\r\n\n  Line 674: [25/04/2024, 21:36:57] Andie: That the human projecting innit\r\n\n  Line 868: [29/04/2024, 20:35:32] Andie: Thats where I see that purpose project bring us all real value\r\n\n  Line 2231: As a recent graduate in Information and Communication Technology, I witnessed firsthand the struggles students face in traditional classroom settings. That's why for my final year project, I developed a generative AI prototype to personalize learning and provide on-demand assistance to coding students I was teaching. \n\n  Line 2486: Regarding the chatbot and website UX improvement project, I think it would be a great opportunity for you to contribute your skills and experience. I'll introduce you to my son Antoni, who manages the website. In the meantime, please go ahead and research Wix chatbot integration options and prepare a document outlining your initial ideas and a proposed agenda for our discussion.\n\n  Line 2490: In addition to the projects we discussed, I'd like to offer you some work experience over the summer. This would be a great opportunity for you to gain hands-on experience in a professional setting and learn more about our company and the work we do.\n\n  Line 2548: [25/06/2024, 17:40:52] Andie: The Alacrity Foundation offers a graduate programme where they provide recent graduates with practical training and mentorship. As part of this programme, participants receive a stipend of £1,500 per month. This stipend is intended to support graduates while they develop their skills and work on real-world projects.\r\n\n  Line 2691: [26/06/2024, 08:46:48] Andie: https://www.anthropic.com/news/projects\r\n\n  Line 2976: I'm reaching out because I'm currently working on an exciting podcast project with my colleague, Marquis, who works for Business Wales. When I mentioned your background to him, he was immediately interested in exploring the possibility of your involvement.\n\n  Line 2990: Additionally, as a USW alumnus, I'm curious if you might have insights about accessing the university's podcast facilities for this project.\n\n  Line 3175: [12/07/2024, 14:04:52] Andie: His goal is to understand the overarching concepts and theories behind these technologies so he can make informed decisions when building and launching his own AI-based project.\r\n\n  Line 3367: [12/07/2024, 18:20:35] Andie: My role will be to share a bit about my own background as a current student who did my dissertation in this area and has some experience working with local schools on AI/tech projects.\r\n\n  Line 4316: [30/07/2024, 10:32:27] Andie: but elaborate more on the HOW I could grt to that simpler explanation, this stems from a problem I observed trying to get teachers and students to enjoy online project Youtube walkthroughs delivered however by different nationals often Indian with a bit of a thick accent and unfortunately not the most crystal clear audio setup and so the experience turns sour even though the content is premium ‎<This message was edited>\r\n\n  Line 4350: [30/07/2024, 11:36:15] Andie: I mention programmers because, in the new A-level Digital Technologies curriculum, students are assigned a project where they must identify a local business that needs an e-commerce website and build it from scratch. An important aspect of this project is the evaluation process they undergo to determine whether a business would benefit from an e-commerce solution. This evaluation is crucial for developing their ability to think independently. ‎<This message was edited>\r\n\n  Line 4359: [30/07/2024, 11:59:05] Andie: Our platform is an EdTech solution designed to upskill teachers in Wales. It addresses a key problem we’ve observed: many online educational resources, such as YouTube project walkthroughs, are often delivered by presenters with thick accents and unclear audio, which can make high-quality content hard to engage with. Our platform focuses on Continuing Professional Development (CPD) for educators, specifically to help them effectively teach the WJEC GCE A Level Digital Technology curriculum. We offer high-quality, self-paced video training and supplementary materials with clear audio and delivery, ensuring a better learning experience. Our goal is to enhance teachers' digital skills, improve accessibility, and support Welsh language preservation, especially in rural areas.\r\n\n  Line 4400: [30/07/2024, 12:16:12] Andie: *Assessment Changes:* The use of onscreen exams and project work may require teachers to adapt their teaching and assessment strategies.\r\n\n  Line 5282: [10/09/2024, 11:14:10] Andie: and I am commissioning web dev work to my web dev friend I currently live with, he then does part pro bono and depending on the complexity of the project at time charge a fee the rest the hosting platform he pays for monthly gives him a percentage of every single clients he onboard the website he built for them\r\n\n  Line 5334: [10/09/2024, 17:40:45] Andie: At the moment I am taking one project at time through that process to make it less overwhelm\r\n\n  Line 5381: The platform, founded by Andie, who has a strong background in educational technology and learning design, is not just about building skills. Andie’s vision is to help bridge the digital divide and tackle digital poverty, particularly in rural communities. Drawing from her own learning experiences and work with projects like Technocamps, she’s committed to making a lasting impact in Welsh education.\n\n  Line 5398: The platform, founded by Andie, who has a strong background in educational technology and learning design, is not just about building skills. Andie’s vision is to help bridge the digital divide and tackle digital poverty, particularly in rural communities. Drawing from her own learning experiences and work with projects like Technocamps, she’s committed to making a lasting impact in Welsh education.\n\n  Line 5932: Unfortunately, regarding the LinkedIn opportunity you tagged me in, they informed me that eligibility required being backed by an academic institution or organisation-led, IP-protected solution, rather than a personally-owned project. ‎<This message was edited>\r\n\n\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Downloads\\_chat 4 (1).txt:\n  Line 36: [03/05/2024, 20:57:39] Andie: I am soon gonna be starting a community project in collaboration with Researchers at a Black Market Research company based in London called ClearView btw, so might get a little busy. But not tremendously. Ive got about 6 trainings to go through that have been spread out in 2hrs per training session. Over May and join. Heres the project that they appointed me as Community Researcher\r\n\n  Line 1213: [25/05/2024, 13:42:01] Andie: they are doing short films projection, going on tour around community spaces like the one I am in rn\r\n\n  Line 1218: [25/05/2024, 13:43:59] ~ Juanee Scott: I won’t be able to attend it unfortunately. I’m prepping for a shoot tomorrow in London for my own project!\r\n\n  Line 1316: [26/05/2024, 10:54:34] Andie: So he offered me a summer project with his company\r\n\n  Line 1402: [28/05/2024, 18:29:39] ~ Juanee Scott: I was focused on the project!\r\n\n  Line 1532: [29/05/2024, 15:14:48] Andie: as you should be, I really enjoyed taking in your dissertation project, ur creative mind Sharon hurts my brain and they way u dont play with colours eh\r\n\n  Line 2089: [04/06/2024, 17:44:48] Marquis A. Caines (BYPCardiff): I got some projects going at the minute\r\n\n  Line 2095: [04/06/2024, 17:45:38] Marquis A. Caines (BYPCardiff): I need to block out time to focus on these projects\r\n\n  Line 2437: [05/06/2024, 11:38:20] Sharonita 