      "text": "The user is asking if the ProLector tool they created on Replit will work based on everything we've discussed. They want me to confirm whether their tool can actually do what we've been talking about - voice cloning, visual prosody, shadowing, etc.\n\nLet me look at what we've established:\n1. ProLector is a teleprompter with AI voice read-along\n2. It uses Kokoro-82M for TTS\n3. It has voice cloning capability\n4. It has loop/rehearse features\n5. It can set WPM speed\n\nThe user wants to know if this will work for mastering English prosody, regional dialects, etc.\n\nLooking at the code we read earlier, ProLector does have:\n\n\n- A teleprompter with adjustable speed\n- AI Voice Read-Along using Kokoro-82M\n- Voice cloning with SpeechT5 models\n- Loop/rehearse functionality\n- Multiple voice options\n\nSo the core features they need are already there - voice cloning, adjustable pacing, and the ability to practice loops. Now I'm checking whether the implementation actually supports the specific use cases we discussed, like visual prosody tooltips and regional accent training.\n\nThe main gaps I'm seeing are that the visual tooltips would require additional development, and while Kokoro-82M works well for voice cloning, it's not ideal for capturing regional dialects since it only has a limited set of built-in voices. The real-time keystroke marking for error tracking isn't implemented yet either. So the foundation is solid, but there are some key features still missing before it can fully deliver on everything we outlined.",
