    {
      "type": "answer",
      "text": "All done. Pushed to `andiekobbietks/prolector-yourvoice-perfected`.\n\n## What's new\n\n### Deepgram Aura (Cloudflare Workers AI)\n\n| Feature | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| Engine | 6th engine in SyllabusMirror, type `\"deepgram-aura\"` |\n| Routing | Cloud fallback — kicks in when local engines are slow (RTF > 0.7) or for short sentences when explicitly enabled |\n| Cost | Free 10K neurons/day on Cloudflare |\n| Config | Account ID + API Token in teleprompter side panel, persisted to localStorage |\n| Voices | 8 options: asteria, luna, stella, athena, hera, orion, arcas, perseus |\n| Lens color | Cyan (`border-cyan-500`) |\n\n### Score View (`/score`)\n\nThe pronunciation workbook. Script laid out horizontally with:\n\n- **Pitch contour** — smooth bezier SVG curve above each sentence, like a melody line on a lead sheet. Hz values annotated at each word.\n- **Stress badges** — ● primary, ○ secondary, · unstressed\n- **Vowel compression bars** — colored line under each word: green (full) → yellow → orange → red (schwa)\n- **Coarticulation bridges** — →r, ↻, ɾ, ⊘, ≈ annotated at word boundaries\n- **WPM presets** — TED Talk (120), Tutorial (135), BBC News (155), Audiobook (150)\n- **Zoom** — adjust character width for dense/airy layouts\n- **Annotations toggle** — hide all overlays for clean reading mode\n- **Playback** — Space to play/pause, R to reset, ↑↓ for WPM\n\nAccessible in the nav bar as \"Score\".",
      "timestamp": 1781546753596
    },
    {
      "type": "thought",
      "text": "All done. Let me give a summary.",
      "timestamp": 1781546757985
    },
    {
      "type": "user-query",
      "text": "anything of which understand is assumed in this site? pls tell me all that is",
      "timestamp": 1781547907624
    },
    {
      "type": "answer",
      "text": "Good question. Here's everything the site assumes about the user without stating it:\n\n## Language Assumptions\n\n1. **English-only** — All prosody rules (linking-r, intrusion, flap-t, assimilation, elision) are English-specific. No other language is supported.\n2. **Standard British/American accent target** — The WPM benchmarks, stress patterns, and vowel compression models assume you're aiming for RP or General American. No dialect training (Welsh, London, Nottinghamshire) is built in, despite us discussing it.\n3. **CEFR B2+ assumed** — The interface is entirely in English. Technical terms like \"prosody,\" \"coarticulation,\" \"RTF,\" \"WPM,\" \"forced alignment\" are used without explanation. A B1 learner would struggle.\n\n## Content Assumptions\n\n4. **Scripted speech only** — The app is built around reading prepared text aloud. No support for spontaneous speech, improvisation, or conversational practice.\n5. **Public speaking / broadcasting context** — The WPM rubric (120-160), the teleprompter format, the \"broadcast-grade clarity\" language all assume you're performing for an audience, not having a conversation.\n6. **Content creator persona** — The pricing tiers say \"Individual Educator,\" \"Active Course Creator,\" \"Production House.\" The assumption is you're making content for others, not improving your own English for daily life.\n\n## Technical Assumptions\n\n7. **Modern browser** — WebAssembly, Web Audio API, OPFS, MediaRecorder. No fallback for older browsers.\n8. **Microphone access** — Recording features assume you have a mic and are in a quiet space.\n9. **2.2GB download** — First load downloads Kokoro-82M. No warning, no progress indicator mentioned. Assumes fast internet.\n10. **Cloudflare account** — Deepgram Aura requires Account ID + API Token. Assumes you know what Cloudflare Workers AI is.\n\n## Learning Assumptions\n\n11. **Shadowing is the method** — The entire app is built around the Lampariello shadowing method. No alternative learning approaches (grammar study, vocabulary building, conversation practice).\n12. **Prosody over everything** — The app prioritizes rhythm, stress, and intonation. Assumes that's your bottleneck, not vocabulary or grammar.\n13. **Self-directed practice** — No teacher dashboard, no progress tracking, no guided curriculum. Assumes you know what to practice and can self-correct.\n14. **Own-voice benefit assumed** — The \"Auditory Feedforward Training\" section cites Dowrick, Hebb, Hickok & Poeppel. Assumes you buy into this framework without questioning it.\n15. **Immediate feedback desired** — Visual prosody, pitch contours, stress badges all assume you want real-time feedback on your speech, not delayed reflection.\n\n## Design Assumptions\n\n16. **Visual learner** — The Score View, pitch contours, stress badges, vowel compression bars all assume you learn by seeing your speech patterns.\n17. **Data-driven** — RTF metrics, neuron counts, WPM benchmarks, Hz values. Assumes you're comfortable with numbers.\n18. **Dark mode default** — The entire UI is dark-themed. No light mode toggle.\n19. **Desktop-first** — The 420px side panel, horizontal Score View, keyboard shortcuts all assume desktop/laptop use. Mobile is secondary.\n\n## What's Missing\n\n- No explanation of what \"prosody\" means on first visit\n- No onboarding flow for non-technical users\n- No guidance on what WPM to start with\n- No progress tracking across sessions\n- No teacher/classroom mode\n- No non-English language support\n- No dialect selection beyond the 6 Kokoro voices\n\nThe site assumes a technically literate, self-directed English learner who already knows what prosody is, wants to improve their public speaking, and is comfortable configuring Cloudflare API keys. That's a narrow audience.",
      "timestamp": 1781547907656
    },
    {
      "type": "thought",
      "text": "The user is asking about what assumptions are built into the site/app — what knowledge or context is assumed about the user. This is a thoughtful question about the design philosophy and implicit assumptions baked into ProLector.\n\nLet me think through all the assumptions:\n\n1. **Language assumption**: The entire app assumes English. All the prosody rules (linking-r, intrusion, flap-t, assimilation, elision) are English-specific. The stress patterns, vowel compression, and coarticulation detection are all English linguistics. The WPM benchmarks are for English speech.\n\n2. **Accent assumption**: The default voices and prosody models are trained on standard British/American English. There's no built-in support for other English dialects or other languages.\n   \n3. **Scripted speech assumption**: The app is built around reading prepared text aloud, not spontaneous conversation or unscripted delivery.\n\n4. **Performance mode**: Users are training for public speaking, broadcasting, presentations, or audiobook narration — not casual speech.\n\n5. **Hardware requirements**: The browser needs WebAssembly support and enough memory to load the 2.2GB Kokoro model, plus microphone access for recording.\n\n6. **Internet dependency**: Cloudflare hosting is required, though local TTS works offline once the model downloads.\n\n7. **Technical literacy**: Users need to understand basic teleprompter controls and know how to configure API keys for Cloudflare integration.\n\n8. **Content creator audience**: The app assumes users are creating content for others to consume, not just practicing for personal use.\n\n9. **CEFR proficiency**: The interface is entirely in English with technical jargon, targeting intermediate to advanced learners rather than beginners.\n\n10. **Pricing structure**: The tiered pricing assumes users have disposable income and are willing to pay for premium features.\n\n11. **Learning philosophy**: The app defaults to shadowing as the primary learning method, without offering alternatives like grammar study or vocabulary building.\n\n12. **Privacy expectations**: The local-first architecture assumes users value privacy and want to avoid cloud dependencies.\n\n13. **Technical setup**: Users are expected to have a modern browser with WebGPU, WebAssembly, and Web Audio API support.\n\n14. **AI trust**: The app positions AI-optimized text as authoritative, which may not suit all learning contexts.\n\n15. **Prosody focus**: The curriculum prioritizes prosody and delivery over other aspects like grammar or vocabulary.\n\n16. **Self-directed learning**: Users are expected to identify their own mistakes and work through them independently.\n\n17. **Performance pressure**: The teleprompter format assumes users thrive under time pressure and public performance anxiety.\n\n18. **Accent standardization**: The app defaults to Standard British/American English without considering that users might be learning other varieties.\n\n19. **Linguistic terminology**: Users are assumed to understand or want to learn terms like \"prosody,\" \"F0,\" \"coarticulation,\" and \"phoneme.\"\n\n20. **WPM metrics**: The app uses words per minute as the primary measurement, which may not be the most meaningful metric for language learning.\n\n21. **Recording setup**: The app assumes users have a decent microphone and are in a quiet space, which isn't always realistic.\n\n22. **Practice time**: The app is built around intensive, focused practice sessions rather than casual, frequent use.\n\n23. **Feedback expectations**: Users are expected to want immediate, granular feedback on their speech rather than delayed or general feedback.\n\n24. **Visual learning**: The app assumes users are visual learners who benefit from seeing their speech patterns graphically represented.\n\n25. **Audio learning**: The app also assumes users are auditory learners who benefit from hearing model pronunciations.\n\n26. **Kinesthetic learning**: The app assumes users benefit from physically repeating and practicing speech patterns.\n\n27. **Social isolation**: The app is designed for solo practice, not collaborative or social learning.\n\n28. **Device assumptions**: The app assumes users have a computer or tablet, not just a phone.\n\n29. **Browser compatibility**: The app assumes users have a modern browser that supports WebAssembly and Web Audio API.\n\n30. **Learning goals**: The app assumes users want to sound like native speakers rather than maintaining their own accent or identity.\n\nActually, let me reconsider what the user is really asking. They want to know what knowledge or context is assumed about the user visiting the site. Let me focus on the core assumptions:\n\nThe site assumes users can read and understand English well enough to navigate the interface, are interested in improving their English pronunciation and delivery, have some technical comfort with browsers and web apps, and are willing to invest time in deliberate practice. It also assumes users want to sound more like native speakers, have access to recording equipment, and are comfortable with self-directed learning.\n\nThe site doesn't explicitly state these assumptions but they're built into the design and content.",
      "timestamp": 1781547914378
    },
